*If formula_37 is the meeting point between the perpendicular from formula_15 to the line segment formula_30 and the tangent to the circle at formula_16 , then the triangle formula_41 is isosceles, as is easily seen from the construction: formula_42 and formula_43formula_44 . For the previous noted equality between formula_45 and formula_46 then formula_47 and formula_41 is isosceles.
*Drawing from formula_16 the orthogonal segment to formula_30, from formula_15 the straight line tangent to the upper circle, and calling formula_52 the meeting point, one sees that formula_53 is a rhombus using the theorems on angles between parallel lines
*Now consider the velocity formula_54 of formula_16 . It can be seen as the sum of two components, the rolling velocity formula_56 and the drifting velocity formula_57, which are equal in modulus because the circles roll without skidding. formula_57 is parallel to formula_59, while formula_56 is tangent to the lower circle at formula_16 and therefore is parallel to formula_62. The rhombus constituted from the components formula_57 and formula_56 is therefore similar (same angles) to the rhombus formula_65 because they have parallel sides. Then formula_54, the total velocity of formula_16, is parallel to formula_68 because both are diagonals of two rhombuses with parallel sides and has in common with formula_69 the contact point formula_16. Thus the velocity vector formula_54 lies on the prolongation of formula_69 . Because formula_54 is tangent to the cycloid at formula_16, it follows that also formula_69 coincides with the tangent to the lower cycloid at formula_16.
*Analogously, it can be easily demonstrated that formula_69 is orthogonal to formula_78 (the other diagonal of the rhombus).
*This proves that the tip of a wire initially stretched on a half arch of the lower cycloid and fixed to the upper circle at formula_15 will follow the point along its path &quot;without changing its length&quot; because the speed of the tip is at each moment orthogonal to the wire (no stretching or compression). The wire will be at the same time tangent at formula_16 to the lower arc because of the tension and the facts demonstrated above. (If it were not tangent there would be a discontinuity at formula_16 and consequently unbalanced tension forces.)

